Gas and ice grains in the Enceladean plume, at least to a greater part, is material from the subsurface ocean (Postberg et al. 2009, 2011b, 2018b,a; Waite et al. 2009, 2017). The mechanical and thermodynamic driver of the plume is evaporation of ocean water from the water table inside back-pressured vents at temperatures close to the freezing point of the salty (≈1–2%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\approx 1\mbox{--}2\%$\end{document} salinity) and alkaline (pH 8.5–12\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$8.5\mbox{--}12$\end{document}) water (Postberg et al. 2009; Hsu et al. 2015; Glein et al. 2015). An average total amount of about 300kg/s\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$300~\mbox{kg/s}$\end{document} of water vapour (Hansen et al. 2019) escapes into the plume, setting a lower limit for the evaporative flux below. The vapour is partially redeposited onto the vents’ ice walls (Ingersoll and Pankine 2010; Ingersoll and Nakajima 2016) and also partially condenses to tiny ice grains with sizes mostly below 1μm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
